Breer is a social enterprise that focuses on reducing the huge problem of food wastage in Hong Kong. The problem of food wastage and waste disposal has exponentially risen over the last decade, with the total amount of landfill space available almost used up. Breer is a revolution that helps solve this problem by reintroducing wasted or otherwise leftover bread into the supply chain by breaking it down into its raw ingredients and converting it into their own local craft beer. As we started our Good Seed Journey, we decided to speak to different stakeholders to understand their experiences. In an event organized by the Zubin Foundation,
we learnt that due to Covid-19, many ethnic minorities lost their job. Not only that, in our discussion with HKDA, we learnt that social interaction and integration has reduced since the pandemic. Owing to this, we decided to incorporate these two members as our key
beneficiaries, involving them in every step of the process. Now, Breer is the face of our business: our main aim is to foster inclusion and promote empowerment.

data.description:
In 2012, a fund of HK$500 million was set up to catalyze the growth of social enterprises. The fund is the Social Innovation and Entrepreneurship Development Fund (the SIE Fund).
The Fund’s objective is to establish and support schemes and experiments with a view to attracting, inspiring, or nurturing social entrepreneurs to develop innovations that aim at creating social impact and social capital for the purpose of poverty relief in Hong Kong.
This research is conducted through the Good Seed Program, the earliest (started in 2015) and the main incubator for social startups funded by the SIE Fund. The program provides incubation and seed funding for early-stage social startups.
The research analyzed business proposals of 268 social startups in Hong Kong submitted to Good Seed Program, their survival status and critical incidents during the scaling processes revealed the roles of idiosyncratic and traditional ecosystem resource endowments including intermediary services, funding support, digital infrastructures, market infrastructures and public subsidies for social enterprise products and services, and institutional mechanisms such as shared discourse and values and arrangement

media.text: Cell nodes connect people cybernetically into small-word and global networks

pageContent.subText: The cell incubator will bring founders together to launch the first 10 cells through ixo.world. This will demonstrate how cyber-cellular organisations operate. Each cell will have an impact mission and implement at least one project, with accountable targets. Up to 100 applications will be accepted for the first cohort. The top 10 candidates will be invited to join the incubator. The work of this incubator will be considered done only after at least 8 of the teams have achieved their cell recruitment and project performance targets. On successful completion, cells will be rewarded with an economic stake in the ixo.world relayer node, valued at 5,000 Euro.
pageContent.subTitle: Mission
pageContent.text: The Cell Incubator connects a network of teams who are founding their own cells to implement pilot projects through ixo.world. A cyber-cell is a highly networked, intelligent form of organisation. This enables people to achieve a shared mission through self-coordination, self-governance, sharing common resources and having access to the same sources of truth. Cells mimic how nature operates in ways that are decentralised, self-regulating and adaptive. The human immune system is a great example. This organisational model is popular with high-performing teams. Now we can virtualise and augment cellular orgranisations with cybernetic capabilites, so that they can sense and respond much more rapidly and precisely to changes in the world. Members of the incubator cell will support each other to learn about, develop and implement cybernetic tools for their use-cases, using artificial intelligence, blockchain smart contracts, p2p communications, electronic rights and decentralised finance mechanisms.

pageContent.subText: Cell nodes are the digital infrastructure for all types of cellular organisations. These are decentralised, autonomous data stores with digital agency and cryptographic signing capabilities. Cell nodes enable data to be communicated quickly and securely through webs of trust. All participants in a cell have access to the same information and share intelligence both within their own cell node and with other organisations, through Internet of Impact networks.The digital artefacts created by a cell (such as Project Documents) are stored in the node as stateful records which are referenced in a distributed ledger. Public metadata are stored using the Interplanetary File System (IPFS). This allows cell nodes to retain a form of memory that can be stigmergically shared and rapidly amplified when cells need to be replicated or re-activated.

data.description: Aging, loud noise, injury, stroke, infection, tumour, or inborn issue could result in hearing loss in different degrees. One of the easiest solutions to hearing loss is to wear a hearing aid. Hearing aids are electronics devices which can reproduce an amplified sound. There are different types and styles of hearing aids, such as Body-Worn (BW), Behind-The-Ear (BTE), Receiver-In-Canal (RIC), In-The-Ear (ITE), In-The-Canal (ITC), Completely-In-Canal (CIC), and Invisible-In-Canal (IIC). Traditional hearing aids are using analog circuits to simply amplify the sound while most of the modern hearing aids are using digital signal processing (DSP) to give advanced features like frequency shift, noise suppression and echo reduction.

data.description: G6PD缺乏症（G6PD Deficiency），中文全名為葡萄糖六磷酸去氫酵素缺乏症，俗稱蠶豆症（Favism），這是一種常見的先天性基因缺乏疾病，以男性患者較多。G6PD為一種酵素，在人體進行新陳代謝時保護紅血球，以對抗某些氧化物。當蠶豆症患者受到嚴重感染或接觸某些特定氧化物時，身體缺乏生產G6PD的細胞，不足以抵擋活性氧破壞紅血球，繼而產生溶血反應。目前為止，G6PD缺乏症已知有400多種基因變異。蠶豆症不能根治，至今仍無法用藥物治療，患者只能終身避免接觸某些物品，最常見包括蠶豆及樟腦丸；中藥如金銀花、臘梅花、牛黃、黃連、珍珠末；西藥如阿士匹靈，都有可能引起溶血反應。此時，患者會出現面色蒼白、疲倦、食欲不振、眼白皮膚變黃、茶色尿；嚴重的話，更可能會有昏迷，甚至死亡風險。
